definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines cow life from the prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Cow life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends at birth.

comments: Bovine gestation is 277 days (about 9 months) (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Bos_taurus). Depending on the breed, the gestation time slightly varies (see http://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development). Gestational length is commonly calculated based on recorded insemination (see PMID:30452469), so actually this is the fetal age.

definition.val: Cow developmental stage that covers the period from birth until 1.5 years old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: Female cows reach sexual maturity by 548 days of age(see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Bos_taurus).

definition.val: Cow developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult cow, which is usually over 1.5 years old.
Mature stage that refers to a cow who is over 1.5 and under 12 years old, the usual upper limit for breeding age.

comments: Females appear to remain fertile for about 12 years (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Bos_taurus).

definition.val: Mature stage that refers to a cow who is over 12 years old, the usual upper limit for breeding age.

comments: Cows have been known to live over 20 years.

definition.val: Embryo development period during the first 3 months of gestation, up to day 90 of development.

comments: Toward the end of the third month (60 to 90 days), the four stomachs may be recognized. The fetus measures 14 cm. in length. The scrotum is present (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the second trimester of gestation, from over day 90 up to day 180 of development.

comments: At end of the sixth month, the eyelashes are more developed. The foetus is about 46 cm. long. The whole body is still naked excepting the lips and eyelids (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the last trimester of gestation, from the seventh month (over 180 days) of development until birth.

comments: A few long hairs appear at the end of the tail, and in the beginning of the ninth month, the whole body is covered with hair and increases greatly in size. The fetus measures from 80 to 100 cm. In the beginning of the tenth month, the fetus becomes mature. (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the first month of gestation.

comments: The embryo is 9 to 10 mm long and the first signs of extremities appear (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the second month of gestation (30 to 60 days).

comments: The extremities develop. The pharyngeal cleft closes in the beginning of this month. First indication of the hoof. (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the third month of gestation (60 to 90 days).

comments: The extremities develop. The pharyngeal cleft closes in the beginning of this month. First indication of the hoof. (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the fourth month of gestation (90 to 120 days).

comments: In the beginning of the fourth month the hoofs become quite distinct; they are firm, non-transparent, and have a yellow color. The fetus is about 24 cm. long (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the fifth month of gestation (120 to 150 days).

comments: In the beginning of the fifth month the first tentaculse (tactile hairs) appear on the lips, chin, upper eyelid, and orbital arch. The teats are plainly visible. The testicles descend into the scrotum. The fetus is about 35 cm. long (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the sixth month of gestation (150 to 180 days).

comments: The eyelashes are more developed. The foetus is about 46 cm. long. The whole body is still naked excepting the lips and eyelids (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

definition.val: Embryo development period during the seventh month of gestation (180 to 210 days).

comments: At the end of this month a few long hairs appear at the end of the tail; also hairs about the coronet and on the spots where the horns appear. The foetus is about 60 cm. long (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

nodes.lbl: eighth month of gestation cow stage

definition.val: Embryo development period during the eighth month of gestation (210 to 240 days).

comments: The back begins to be covered with hair, also along the edges of the ears (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).

nodes.lbl: ninth and over month of gestation

definition.val: Embryo development period during the ninth month of gestation (over 240 days) until birth.

comments: In the beginning of the ninth month, the whole body is covered with hair and increases greatly in size, and at beginning of the tenth month, the fetus becomes mature (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php?title=Bovine_Development#General_Overview).
